    <a name="6">Transfer to another Program</a></span>

    <span class="style21">

    <br />
    <br />



    </span>



    </span>



    <span class="style20">



    <span class="style22">

    When a particular program does not seem suitable for a student's skills and abilities, the student should consider transfering to another, more appropriate program. The sooner such transfers are done, the fewer credits that will be lost. Historically, for example, it is common for students to transfer between the CPD/CPA programs and the CNS/CTY programs after first semester, and since only one course is different between the two program streams, such transfer students lose only one credit. Similar transfers later on would result in more credit loss because the program streams diverge after first semester. Transfers from diploma to degree programs typically also result in some credit loss even if the content of the programs is similar, because the level of difficulty is typically higher in the degree programs. Students who feel that their current program is not suitable should consult with a program coordinator, to discuss the appropriateness, availability and transferability of other programs either within the School or elsewhere in the College.
    


